Abia state government has threatened to close down any churches that violated the COVID-19 prevention protocols during its streams of service or other programmes in the state. Secretary to the state government (SSG), Barrister Chris Ezem stated this while speaking on update on COVID-19 in the state in Umuahia, the state capital, saying the restriction on interstate movement is still in force. He maintained that in pursuance of this, the committee will intensify its monitoring of churches on compliance with the protocols even in the remotest part of the state for the good of the people. Similarly, the state Inter-Ministerial Committee on COVID-19 has directed its enforcement team to prosecute any persons caught walking along the street without wearing a face mask before a mobile court. Ezem, who is also the chairman of the committee, frowned at the manner people violate the protocols, made it clear that the government is committed to ensure the control of the spread of the virus in the state. The state scribe therefore enjoined the transition committee chairmen of the 17 local government councils of the state to, without exception, ensure that the COVID-19 protocols are ensured in their areas. Reacting to the directives, the transition committee chairman of Ikwuano local government council, Barrister Stanley Ojigbo described it as a welcome development in the overall interest of the people. Ojigbo said since the lockdown of the state which is now in its third month, the council, with the cooperation of the staff and the traditional rulers have been doing all they could to prevent its spread. “We have not let down our guard against the pandemic. We have been using every available opportunity and resources to take the campaign to every nook and cranny of the area,” he said. According to him, “Being aware of our location as a boundary area, we cannot afford to make the mistake of compromising the border against the lockdown order.